<section id="command-setscreencolor">
<title>SETSCREENCOLOR</title>
<indexterm><primary>SETSCREENCOLOR</primary></indexterm>
<indexterm><primary>SETSC</primary></indexterm>

<variablelist>

<varlistentry><term>Synopsis</term>
<listitem>
<synopsis><command>SETSCREENCOLOR</command> <parameter>color</parameter>
<command>SETSCREENCOLOUR</command> <parameter>color</parameter>
<command>SETSC</command> <parameter>color</parameter></synopsis>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>

<varlistentry><term>Description</term>
<listitem>
<para>
Sets the screen background color to <parameter>color</parameter> and changes the entire screen to that color.
The <parameter>color</parameter> input may either be a color index or a color vector.
A color index is a number from 0 - 15.
A color vector is a list of [red green blue] intensities, each in the range of 0 - 255.
For an explanation of the <parameter>color</parameter> input, see the section on <link linkend="using-color">Using Color</link>.
</para>

</listitem>
</varlistentry>
<varlistentry><term>Example</term>
<listitem>

<programlisting><userinput>SETSCREENCOLOR [0 0 0]
SETPENCOLOR [255 255 255]
REPEAT 4 [FORWARD 100 RIGHT 90]
CLEAN</userinput>
</programlisting>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>
</variablelist>

</section>
